description: Do not use em dashes (—) in copy, UI strings, or comments; use commas, periods, or colons instead.
alwaysApply: true
---

# No em dashes

- **Do not** use the Unicode em dash character (U+2014, `—`) anywhere in this project: marketing copy, UI strings, meta tags, comments, or docs.
- **Prefer**: a comma, period, colon, or parentheses depending on the sentence. For name/location lines (e.g. attributions), use a comma: `Sarah, 28, London`.
- **Hyphen-minus** (`-`) is fine for compound words and ranges; this rule targets em dashes only.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
<p>We ship fast — without breaking things.</p>

// ✅ GOOD
<p>We ship fast, without breaking things.</p>
```

```html
<!-- ❌ BAD -->
<meta property="og:title" content="bwend — The dating app" />

<!-- ✅ GOOD -->
<meta property="og:title" content="bwend: The dating app" />
```

When editing existing text, replace any `—` with punctuation that matches the tone of the sentence.
